    <!-- INGREDIENT BOX -->
    <div class="ing-box">
      <h4>Collagen Peptides Explained: Types, Sources, and Clinical Dosing</h4>
      <p>Not all collagen supplements are created equal. The source, type, hydrolysis level, and dose determine whether a collagen gummy delivers measurable beauty benefits or is simply expensive candy.</p>

      <div class="vs-strip">
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Bovine Collagen (Type I & III)</strong>
          <p>Sourced from cowhide. The most common and cost-effective collagen source. Provides Type I (skin, hair, nails) and Type III (skin elasticity, blood vessels). Well-studied for skin hydration and elasticity at 2.5-10g daily.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Marine Collagen (Type I)</strong>
          <p>Sourced from fish scales and skin. Lower molecular weight for faster absorption. Primarily Type I collagen. Some studies suggest 1.5x faster plasma absorption vs. bovine. Pescatarian-friendly but not vegan.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Chicken Collagen (Type II)</strong>
          <p>Sourced from chicken sternum cartilage. Primarily Type II collagen for joint health. UC-II (undenatured) at 40mg daily is clinically studied for joint mobility. Not the optimal choice for beauty-focused supplementation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="vs-item">
          <strong>Clinical Dosing Range</strong>
          <p>2.5g per day: minimum effective dose for skin elasticity (8-12 weeks). 5g per day: optimal for combined skin, hair, and nail benefits. 10g per day: maximum studied dose, primarily in powder form. Most gummies deliver 2.5-3g per serving.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <span class="tip-box-ico">&#128138;</span>
        <p><strong>Absorption maximizer:</strong> Take collagen gummies on an empty stomach or between meals for optimal peptide absorption. Vitamin C consumed at the same time (or included in the gummy) enhances the hydroxylation step required for functional collagen fiber assembly. Avoid taking collagen with high-protein meals, as other amino acids compete for the same intestinal transporters.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="warn-box">
        <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
        <p><strong>Vegan collagen does not exist yet:</strong> Despite marketing claims, there is no plant-based collagen available at clinically relevant doses. "Vegan collagen" products contain collagen-boosting ingredients (vitamin C, silica, amino acids) that support the body's own collagen production but do not provide preformed collagen peptides. Fermentation-derived recombinant collagen is in development but is not yet commercially available in gummy format.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- HOW WE TESTED -->
    <div class="tested-box">
      <h3>How We Tested These Collagen Gummies</h3>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Purchased independently.</strong> Every product was purchased at full retail price through Amazon or the brand's direct website. No product was provided free of charge, and no brand was informed of this evaluation in advance.</li>
        <li><strong>Verified collagen type and dose.</strong> We analyzed the supplement facts panel of each product to confirm the collagen source (bovine, marine, or chicken), collagen type (I, II, III), and the hydrolyzed peptide dose per serving against label claims.</li>
        <li><strong>Assessed third-party testing.</strong> We contacted each manufacturer to request certificates of analysis from independent laboratories. Products with USP Verification, NSF certification, or verifiable COAs received higher scores in our quality assurance rating.</li>
        <li><strong>Evaluated supporting ingredients.</strong> We scored each product on the inclusion of clinically relevant cofactors — vitamin C (essential for collagen synthesis), hyaluronic acid (hydration), and biotin (keratin support) — and whether their doses were meaningful or token amounts.</li>
        <li><strong>Conducted a 12-week consumer panel.</strong> Six members of our editorial team used each collagen gummy daily for 12 weeks and documented subjective changes in skin texture, nail strength, and hair condition using standardized evaluation criteria and photographs taken under consistent lighting.</li>
        <li><strong>Calculated long-term value.</strong> Cost per serving was computed using the retail price at the time of testing divided by servings per container. We calculated the cost per gram of collagen peptides to enable accurate cross-product comparison independent of bottle size and serving count.</li>
      </ol>
